/***************************************** JAVA *****************************************/

Optimal Approach - we are using two pointer techique for getting the Height is limited by the shorter line, and then we shrink the pointers inward 
                    to get the maxArea.

class Solution {
    public int maxArea(int[] height) {
        int n = height.length;
        // Two pointers: one at the beginning, one at the end
        int i = 0, j = n - 1;
        // Variable to store the maximum water area found
        int maxWater = 0;
        // Continue until the two pointers meet
        while (i < j) {
            // Width of the container
            int w = j - i;
            // Height is limited by the shorter line
            int h = Math.min(height[i], height[j]);
            // Area formed between the two lines
            int area = w * h;
            // Update maximum area
            maxWater = Math.max(maxWater, area);
            // Move the pointer pointing to the shorter line
            // Because moving the taller one cannot increase area
            if (height[i] > height[j]) {
                j--;
            } else {
                i++;
            }
        }
        // Return the maximum water that can be contained
        return maxWater;
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(N),
Space Complexity :- O(1),
